---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import { frontmatter as nowFrontmatter } from '../content/now.md';

const errands = await getCollection('errands');
const essays = await getCollection('essays');
const threads = await getCollection('threads');

const errandCount = errands.length;
const essayCount = essays.length;
const essayDummy = essays.filter((e) => e.data.dummy).length;
const threadCount = threads.length;
const threadDummy = threads.filter((t) => t.data.dummy).length;

const nowDummy = (nowFrontmatter as { dummy?: boolean }).dummy === true;
const nowLastUpdated = new Date(nowFrontmatter.last_updated);
const today = new Date();
const daysSinceNow = Math.floor(
  (today.getTime() - nowLastUpdated.getTime()) / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24)
);
const nowStale = daysSinceNow >= 30;
const nowLabel =
  daysSinceNow === 0
    ? 'updated today'
    : daysSinceNow === 1
    ? 'updated 1 day ago'
    : `updated ${daysSinceNow} days ago`;

const formatCount = (label: string, count: number, dummy: number) => {
  const noun = count === 1 ? label : `${label}s`;
  if (dummy === 0) return `${count} ${noun}`;
  if (dummy === count) return `${count} ${noun} (all dummy)`;
  return `${count} ${noun} (${dummy} dummy)`;
};

const stats = [
  formatCount('errand', errandCount, 0),
  formatCount('essay', essayCount, essayDummy),
  formatCount('thread', threadCount, threadDummy),
  `/now ${nowDummy ? '(dummy) ' : ''}${nowLabel}`,
];

const starterPrompt = `I'm working on preritkhanna.com — my personal site / multi-mode notebook, deployed at https://preritkhanna.pages.dev (auto-deploys on push to main).

Read these docs in order before doing anything:
1. VISION.md — the why
2. AGENTS.md — the working agreement (rules + voice + don'ts)
3. DESIGN.md — visual system + tokens
4. ARCHITECTURE.md — schemas + technical spine
5. WORKFLOW.md — operating loop
6. PRD.md — current phase scope
7. ROADMAP.md — what's coming
8. https://preritkhanna.pages.dev/handbook/ — my personal handbook (private/unlinked page, the practical "how to actually use this" layer in my voice)

What I want to do today: [REPLACE WITH TODAY'S TASK]

The non-negotiables (from AGENTS.md):
- URLs are forever. Don't break /errands/2026-05-ship-v0/ or any other shipped URL.
- Don't add libraries without asking. The dependency list is small on purpose.
- Don't ship empty modes. A new section earns its launch by having content.
- Schemas are gates. Validate at build time. Append-only updates on errands.
- Voice: earnest, unembarrassed, allergic to performance. Funny is fine; defensive hedging of ambition is not.

Just-in-time handoff rule: Pause and ask whenever a step needs me — picking copy, choosing options, anything outside your sandbox. Don't surprise me, don't batch asks at the start, don't proceed with placeholders. One specific question at the right moment.

Don't push without explicit confirmation. Cloudflare auto-deploys on push to main, so each push is a public release.

Begin by reading the docs. Confirm when done, then propose what to do for today's task.`;
---

<Base title="Handbook" description="Personal handbook." noindex={true}>
  <header class="cover">
    <h1>Handbook</h1>
    <p class="lede">A note from past me to future me. About this site, and how to use it.</p>
  </header>

  <hr />

  <article class="prose">
    <section class="dashboard" aria-label="Quick reference">
      <p class="dashboard-intro small muted">If you only have 30 seconds, this is the whole site. Read the prose underneath when you need depth.</p>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>Where the site is right now</h3>
        <p class="stats">
          {stats.map((s, i) => (
            <>
              {i > 0 && <span class="stat-sep" aria-hidden="true"> · </span>}
              <span class={i === stats.length - 1 && nowStale ? 'stat stale' : 'stat'}>{s}</span>
            </>
          ))}
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>The loop</h3>
        <div class="loop">
          <div class="step">Edit in Obsidian</div>
          <span class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
          <div class="step">Save</div>
          <span class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
          <div class="step">Commit all changes</div>
          <span class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
          <div class="step">Push</div>
          <span class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
          <div class="step done">Live in ~60s</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>The modes (live, with current state)</h3>
        <div class="modes-grid">
          <a class="mode-card" href="/">
            <div class="mode-name">/</div>
            <p>The cover. Name, intro, "currently," modes list, on-ramp.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">intro is my draft</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/about/">
            <div class="mode-name">/about</div>
            <p>The self. Origin, beliefs, influences, reversals, colophon.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">mostly dummy</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/errands/">
            <div class="mode-name">/errands</div>
            <p>Projects in motion. The trunk. Each errand is one URL forever.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-live">real content</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/essays/">
            <div class="mode-name">/essays</div>
            <p>Long-form thinking. Drafts are labeled, never hidden.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">first essay dummy</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/threads/">
            <div class="mode-name">/threads</div>
            <p>Narrated domains. Each has a "why this pulls me" body.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">all 3 dummy</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/now/">
            <div class="mode-name">/now</div>
            <p>Current snapshot. Update whenever something changes.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">dummy</span>
          </a>
          <a class="mode-card" href="/guild/">
            <div class="mode-name">/guild</div>
            <p>The recruiting layer. Crew Calls auto-aggregates from errands.</p>
            <span class="mode-status status-dummy">boons + conversations dummy</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>The discipline (the rules behind everything)</h3>
        <div class="discipline-pills">
          <span class="pill">URLs are forever</span>
          <span class="pill">Empty modes don't ship</span>
          <span class="pill">Updates are append-only</span>
          <span class="pill">State ambition flat</span>
          <span class="pill">No empty frontmatter</span>
          <span class="pill">After phase ships, write before building</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>What goes where (decision tree)</h3>
        <table class="decision">
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>A new project</td><td>→</td><td><a href="/errands/"><code>/errands/</code></a> &nbsp; <code>YYYY-MM-slug.md</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>A piece of long-form writing</td><td>→</td><td><a href="/essays/"><code>/essays/</code></a> &nbsp; <code>YYYY-MM-slug.md</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>A new domain you keep returning to</td><td>→</td><td><a href="/threads/"><code>/threads/</code></a> &nbsp; <code>slug.md</code> (no date)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>"Where I am right now"</td><td>→</td><td>edit <code>src/content/now.md</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>A new offer or open conversation</td><td>→</td><td>edit <code>src/pages/guild/boons.astro</code> or <code>conversations.astro</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>An update to an existing project</td><td>→</td><td>append to that errand's <code>updates</code> array</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="dashboard-block">
        <h3>Starter prompt for new Claude Code sessions</h3>
        <p class="prompt-help small muted">Paste this when opening a new session. Replace the <code>[REPLACE WITH TODAY'S TASK]</code> line.</p>
        <div class="prompt-wrap">
          <button id="copy-prompt" class="copy-btn" type="button" data-default="Copy prompt" data-copied="Copied">Copy prompt</button>
          <pre class="prompt-box" id="prompt-text">{starterPrompt}</pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <script>
      const btn = document.getElementById('copy-prompt');
      const text = document.getElementById('prompt-text');
      if (btn && text) {
        btn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
          try {
            await navigator.clipboard.writeText(text.textContent || '');
            const copied = btn.getAttribute('data-copied') || 'Copied';
            const original = btn.getAttribute('data-default') || 'Copy prompt';
            btn.textContent = copied;
            setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = original;
            }, 1600);
          } catch (e) {
            btn.textContent = 'Copy failed';
          }
        });
      }
    </script>

    <section>
      <h2>Welcome back</h2>
      <p>
        If you're reading this, you've probably been away for a while. You
        forgot what this site is. You forgot what the modes are for. You
        forgot how to add a new errand without breaking the build. You're
        looking at the file tree wondering what half of it does.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's fine. This page is the way back. Read it slowly, in order
        the first time. After that, skip to the section you need.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two things to remember before we go further. <strong>One:</strong>
        the site exists for you, not for an audience. The audience is a
        side-effect of doing the work honestly. <strong>Two:</strong> you
        don't have to do everything at once. Most weeks you don't even
        have to open this file. The site is a notebook; notebooks reward
        slowness.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What this site is, in one paragraph</h2>
      <p>
        preritkhanna.com is a multi-mode notebook. It's a single site with
        many sections — projects in motion (errands), long-form writing
        (essays), narrated domains you keep returning to (threads), a
        live snapshot of your present (now), the guild hall where
        collaborators find you (guild), and an evolving picture of who
        you are (about). Eventually it grows to include the things you've
        noticed but not yet engaged with (radar), the canon you'd press
        into someone's hand (library), the books you're processing now
        (learning), the quotes that hit (commonplace), the principles you
        actually live by (principles), the first-principles distillations
        of fields (foundations), and short notes on the world
        (dispatches). Right now only the first set is shipped. The rest
        ship as you grow into them.
      </p>
      <p>
        The site is built on three commitments that are non-negotiable:
        markdown files in git as the spine, URLs that never change once
        published, and schemas as gates that keep content honest. The
        rest is decoration.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The shape, right now</h2>
      <p>
        These are the modes that exist as of today. Each one has a
        specific purpose and a specific kind of writing that goes in. Don't
        try to make one mode do another mode's job — when in doubt, the
        wrong-but-clean home for a piece is better than no home at all,
        and you can move it later.
      </p>

      <h3>/ — the home</h3>
      <p>
        The cover of the notebook. Your name, an intro paragraph that
        names the multi-thing, a one-line "currently" that's actually
        true, a list of the active modes, and a small "if you're new"
        on-ramp. It updates rarely. The intro should be the most
        confident sentence on the site — it sets the voice for everything
        else. If you're tempted to hedge it, don't. State the ambition
        flatly. Naruto says he'll be Hokage flatly.
      </p>

      <h3>/about — the self</h3>
      <p>
        Where readers (and you) get a real picture. Origin (how you got
        here), beliefs (a handful of crisp things you actually think),
        influences (Naruto, Luffy, Da Vinci by name; plus a small list of
        humans whose work models pieces of you), reversals (a running
        list of "I changed my mind about X"), acknowledgments (real
        humans who saw something in you, with permission), an FAQ (small,
        can be empty), and a colophon (what the site is, why this form,
        what it's built with). The reversals section is the most
        interesting one — most people leave it off because admitting you
        were wrong is uncomfortable. Keep it. It's proof you're still
        thinking.
      </p>

      <h3>/errands — Fool's Errand</h3>
      <p>
        Projects. The ones in motion, the ones cooking, the ones
        abandoned. Each errand is one URL that follows the project from
        start to its end-state. The pitch goes in the body — what this
        is, why, what done looks like. The build log goes in the
        <code>updates</code> array, dated, append-only. Decisions and
        gotchas go inline in updates. Code lives in the linked repo, not
        in the errand. Long-form synthesis becomes an essay tagged with
        the errand. Books read for the project go in /learning when
        that's shipped.
      </p>
      <p>
        The errand is the trunk. Other modes are the branches. When you
        ship one, append a final update with what shipped and what
        surprised you. When you abandon one, append a final update with
        the actual reason — be specific. <em>"Lost the energy"</em> isn't
        enough. <em>"The dependency I was relying on got abandoned and
        the rewrite cost more than the project was worth"</em> is enough.
      </p>

      <h3>/essays</h3>
      <p>
        Long-form thinking. Often retrospective on errands. Drafts are
        allowed and labeled as such — don't hide drafts; the
        forcing-function only works if the unfinished is visible.
        Essays are where voice gets calibrated; the first essay sets the
        tone for the whole site. Don't write a manifesto for the first
        one. Write something honest and small.
      </p>

      <h3>/threads</h3>
      <p>
        These are the differentiator. Other polymath sites use tags;
        threads are <em>narrated</em> domains. Each thread you add has a
        2–5 paragraph "why this thread pulls me" body in voice. Then
        every entry across the site that's tagged with this thread
        aggregates onto the thread's page automatically. So a stranger
        reading any one piece can immediately see the surrounding
        intellectual context.
      </p>
      <p>
        Don't add a thread until an interest has earned a name. Tags can
        proliferate cheaply; threads should not. A thread without a body
        is just a tag with airs.
      </p>

      <h3>/now</h3>
      <p>
        A single page that says where you are right now. What you're
        building, what you're reading, what you're chewing on, where you
        physically are if relevant. Update it whenever something changes.
        It's fragmentary and intimate by design. Don't write it like a
        status report. Write it like a postcard to a friend.
      </p>

      <h3>/guild</h3>
      <p>
        The recruiting layer. Three sub-pages. <strong>Crew Calls</strong>
        auto-aggregates from any errand with a <code>looking_for</code>
        field — so if you mention you'd like a collaborator on an errand,
        the recruiting ask shows up in the Guild automatically. You don't
        maintain it separately. <strong>Boons</strong> is what you offer
        — the things you'll help with, the things you know enough to be
        useful at. <strong>Conversations</strong> is standing invitations
        to talk about specific topics, no agenda required.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Luffy frame is: you assemble your crew by helping with
        their quests first. Boons is where you make that real.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The operating loop</h2>
      <p>
        This is the entire workflow when you sit down to write or update
        something. It runs on Obsidian + Obsidian Git + Templater, all
        configured in the project vault.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Open Obsidian. The vault is the project folder.</li>
        <li>Edit a markdown file (or create a new one — folder templates auto-apply the right shape).</li>
        <li>Save (Ctrl+S).</li>
        <li>Command palette (Ctrl+P) → <em>Obsidian Git: Commit all changes</em> → type a message.</li>
        <li>Command palette → <em>Obsidian Git: Push</em>.</li>
        <li>Wait ~60 seconds. Cloudflare rebuilds and deploys to the live site.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That's it. Most of the time you don't open a coding agent at all.
        Coding agents come out only when you want to <em>change the site
        itself</em> — add a new mode, change a layout, add a feature.
        Adding content is just markdown + git push.
      </p>
      <p>
        One caveat to remember: <em>Commit all changes</em> stages every
        untracked file in the repo that isn't in <code>.gitignore</code>.
        If you ever drop a stray file at the project root (chat export,
        scratch note, screenshot), the next "commit all" will sweep it
        into a public commit. The safe pattern is: anything you don't
        want public goes in the <code>private/</code> folder, which is
        already gitignored.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to add a thing — the short version</h2>
      <p>
        Right-click the right folder in Obsidian's file tree. New note.
        Name it correctly (see the conventions just below). The template
        auto-applies. Fill in the frontmatter. Write the body. Commit, push.
      </p>
      <p>
        Filename conventions, internalized once and never thought about
        again:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Errand: <code>YYYY-MM-slug.md</code> in <code>src/content/errands/</code>. All lowercase, hyphens, no spaces, no caps.</li>
        <li>Essay: <code>YYYY-MM-slug.md</code> in <code>src/content/essays/</code>. Same rules.</li>
        <li>Thread: <code>slug.md</code> in <code>src/content/threads/</code> — no date prefix, threads are evergreen.</li>
        <li>Now: just edit the existing <code>src/content/now.md</code>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The filename becomes the URL forever. Pick the slug carefully. A
        bad slug now means a bad URL forever, or a redirect later.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The frontmatter, and why it matters</h2>
      <p>
        Every markdown file in <code>src/content/</code> starts with a
        YAML block between two <code>---</code> lines. This is called
        frontmatter, and it's the structured handle the site uses to
        understand what kind of thing this file is. Title, date, status,
        tags, threads — they all live in frontmatter. The body below
        is what gets rendered as the page.
      </p>
      <p>
        Three rules that will save you from 95% of build failures:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Dates are YAML dates, not strings.</strong> Write
          <code>date: 2026-05-10</code>, not <code>date: "2026-05-10"</code>.
          The quotes turn it into a string and the schema rejects it.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Empty optional fields get deleted, not left blank.</strong>
          If the errand isn't looking for a collaborator yet, delete the
          <code>looking_for:</code> line entirely. Leaving it as
          <code>looking_for:</code> with no value parses as null and
          breaks the build.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Status enums are lowercase.</strong>
          <code>cooking</code>, not <code>Cooking</code>. The schema is
          strict about this on purpose — it makes the data honest.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For the full schema for each mode, see <code>src/content.config.ts</code>
        in the repo. Or see ARCHITECTURE.md, which has them written out.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How the dummy stats work</h2>
      <p>
        The "Where the site is right now" line at the top of this page
        auto-counts your content. It also flags how many entries are
        still scaffold-quality writing rather than the real thing. The
        mechanism is one frontmatter field: <code>dummy: true</code>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>When you replace dummy content with the real version</strong>
        — finally write the real first essay, finally write the
        "why this thread pulls me" body, finally update <code>/now</code>
        with what's actually true — just delete the <code>dummy: true</code>
        line from that file's frontmatter. The stats will reflect it on
        the next deploy. No counter to update manually, no checklist to
        maintain anywhere else.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>When you scaffold a new thing but haven't written the
        real body yet</strong> — say you've named a new thread but the
        body is still a placeholder — add <code>dummy: true</code> to
        the frontmatter. The stats start counting it as dummy
        immediately. When the body is real, drop the line.
      </p>
      <p>
        Schemas where the <code>dummy</code> field is currently active:
        essays, threads, and <code>now.md</code>. Add it to other
        collection schemas in <code>src/content.config.ts</code> if you
        want the same treatment elsewhere.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The discipline (the part that's actually hard)</h2>
      <p>
        The technical setup is easy. Discipline is the hard part. These
        rules are designed in. They keep the site honest over years.
        Soften them and the site degrades into a personal-brand vehicle.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>URLs are forever.</strong> Once a piece is published, its
        URL never changes. If you want to rename a slug, you ship a
        redirect. Sites that survive decades respect their URLs. Don't
        be sloppy here.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Empty modes don't ship.</strong> A path is created the day
        it gets its first real entry. Don't add /library before there's a
        book, don't add /commonplace before there's a quote. The shape
        of the site at any moment should match the actual content.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Updates are append-only.</strong> When you update an
        errand, you append to the <code>updates</code> array. You never
        edit a past update to revise history. If something was wrong,
        you add a new update saying so. The site is the audit log of
        your own thinking. Don't lie to it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The unfinished is visible on purpose.</strong> Drafts are
        labeled drafts. Abandoned errands keep their abandonment notes.
        <code>cooking</code> projects don't pretend they're shipped. The
        forcing-function only works if the incomplete is on display.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Voice: state the ambition flat.</strong> The site lives
        or dies on voice. Earnest, unembarrassed, allergic to
        performance. Self-deprecating humor is fine — that's craft.
        Defensive self-deprecation is not — that's a tic. <em>"I'm
        trying to be many things at once"</em> is the energy. <em>"I'm
        just a humble guy lol probably won't make it but"</em> is not.
        If you find yourself adding qualifiers before stating the
        ambition, delete them.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>After a phase ships, stop building.</strong> The
        temptation is to keep adding modes, redesigning, reworking. The
        rule from VISION.md: after each phase ships, no site work until
        you've added at least three new entries across existing modes.
        Eat the dogfood. Live in the site before you renovate it again.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Pitfalls you've already hit (so you don't again)</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>The .txt-at-the-root pitfall.</strong> You exported a
        chat log from a coding session and left the .txt file at the
        project root. Obsidian Git's "commit all" swept it into a public
        commit. The chat log was now on GitHub. The fix took a force-push
        and a history rewrite. The lesson: anything that's not for the
        public site goes in <code>private/</code> immediately. The folder
        is gitignored; nothing inside it can ever leak.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The empty-frontmatter pitfall.</strong> You created an
        errand in Obsidian without using the template, left
        <code>tagline:</code> blank, and pushed. Cloudflare's deploy
        failed with a Zod validation error. The site stayed on the
        previous build until you fixed the frontmatter. The lesson:
        always use the template (right-click in the right folder; the
        folder template auto-applies), and never push if a frontmatter
        field is empty.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The capitalized-filename pitfall.</strong> You named an
        errand file <code>Portfolio Site - preritkhanna.com.md</code>.
        That filename becomes the URL, with spaces URL-encoded as
        <code>%20</code>. Hideous when shared. The lesson: always
        lowercase, hyphens, <code>YYYY-MM-</code> date prefix for dated
        modes. The title field in frontmatter can be anything pretty;
        the filename has to be a clean slug.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>If something breaks</h2>
      <p>
        Almost every breakage is one of two things: frontmatter
        validation, or git/push trouble. Walk through these in order.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>If the live site stops updating after a push:</strong>
        check Cloudflare Pages' deploy log. The deploy probably failed
        with a Zod error. The error message names the file and the
        field. Open the file, fix the frontmatter, push again.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>If you want to verify before pushing:</strong> run
        <code>npm run build</code> in the project folder. If it passes
        locally, it'll pass on Cloudflare. If it fails, the error tells
        you what to fix.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>If Obsidian Git refuses to push:</strong> usually a sync
        issue — pull first (<em>Obsidian Git: Pull</em>), resolve any
        conflicts, then push. If you're working from one machine only,
        conflicts shouldn't happen; if they do, it means you committed
        from somewhere else (or you have a stale state).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>If you accidentally committed something private:</strong>
        don't panic. Tell a coding agent immediately, before pushing
        again. If it's already pushed, a force-push with history rewrite
        can scrub it from the public repo (this is what we did with the
        .txt file). If the content was sensitive in a way that needed
        rotation (a real secret, not just personal notes), rotate it
        regardless — once something is on GitHub even briefly, assume
        it was scraped.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The cadence</h2>
      <p>
        Most of the rhythm of the site is "update when something
        changes." A few cadences are real and worth respecting:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Whenever something changes:</strong> update /now.
        Append to the relevant errand's updates. If you noticed a person
        or a book or a topic worth remembering, add it to /radar (when
        that's shipped).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Monthly:</strong> write a short reflection essay,
        tagged <code>monthly</code>, dated the last day of the month.
        Look at /garden and abandon what's been stale honestly. This is
        the smallest non-negotiable rhythm. Skipping it once is fine.
        Skipping it for three months means you've drifted; the next one
        is non-negotiable.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Quarterly:</strong> refresh the "If you're new" picks on
        the home page. Look at /bucketlist if shipped. If your thinking
        has shifted on something, add a /about reversal entry.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Annually (December):</strong> write the annual
        reflection essay, tagged <code>annual</code>. This one is
        sacred. It's the story anchor. Re-read all twelve monthly
        reflections first; the annual is the synthesis. Major review of
        /threads (which are still alive?), of /about (does it still
        describe me?), of /library (what earned canon this year?).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The reading list (for when you want depth on something)</h2>
      <p>
        Each of the public docs at the root of the repo has a job. When
        you want to remember <em>why</em>, not <em>how</em>, open one of
        these.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>VISION.md</strong> — when you forget why the site is shaped this way.</li>
        <li><strong>AGENTS.md</strong> — before any AI coding session. The working agreement.</li>
        <li><strong>DESIGN.md</strong> — when making a visual change. Token system, type, color, spacing.</li>
        <li><strong>ARCHITECTURE.md</strong> — when adding a mode, changing a schema, or touching the technical spine.</li>
        <li><strong>WORKFLOW.md</strong> — when your loop has drifted and you want to remember the canonical way.</li>
        <li><strong>PRD.md</strong> — when starting a new phase build. It always describes the current phase only.</li>
        <li><strong>ROADMAP.md</strong> — when wondering what comes after the current phase.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This handbook (the one you're reading) is the practical layer
        that sits on top of all of those. The public docs say what and
        why. This page says <em>how to actually do it</em>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>One last thing</h2>
      <p>
        You built this site to be able to be many things at once,
        publicly, without performing any of them. Most weeks the work is
        small — a paragraph in /now, a quote in /commonplace when that
        ships, a sentence appended to an errand. Some weeks the work is
        bigger — an essay, a new thread, a phase shipping. Both kinds of
        weeks are the work.
      </p>
      <p>
        The site is not the goal. The site is the place the goal lives.
        The goal is to be the kind of person who, in twenty years, has
        a real notebook full of real thinking across many domains —
        because they actually did the work — and can point at it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Don't lose the thread. Write the next paragraph.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <p class="small muted">
      This handbook updates only when a feature ships. If something here
      describes a mode that doesn't exist yet, the handbook is wrong;
      fix it.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

